<paragraph id="8B923690FF8EFF8BC7E3AAF5FB09FEA6" blockId="3.[151,1437,153,682]" pageId="3" pageNumber="449">
<emphasis id="B959EA82FF8EFF8BC7E3AAF5FE36FF72" box="[199,485,153,178]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="449" reason="1">
<emphasis id="B959EA82FF8EFF8BC7E3AAF5FEBAFF71" bold="true" box="[199,361,153,178]" pageId="3" pageNumber="449">Male genitalia</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="13162A15FF8EFF8BC653AAF5FE0BFF72" box="[375,472,153,178]" captionStart="FIGURES 5–8" captionStartId="2.[151,258,1934,1956]" captionTargetBox="[160,1424,187,1894]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[156,1430,182,1907]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 5–8. Lemyra spp., male genitalia. 5, L. persephone, holotype, China, Yunnan, slide AV4756 Volynkin; 2, L. persephone, paratype, China, Yunnan, slide AV4755 Volynkin; 3, L. melanosoma, NE India, slide ZSM Arct. 2019-198; 4, L. melanosoma, China, Yunnan, slide AV5582 Volynkin." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3784034" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3784034/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="449">Figs 5, 6</figureCitation>
).
</emphasis>
Basal section of uncus broad and strongly swollen; distal section narrow, dorso-ventrally flattened, with parallel lateral margins and rectangular tip with rounded corners. Tegumen broad, moderately sclerotised, curved. Juxta moderately sclerotised, strongly broadened and rounded basally and narrowed apically. Vinculum robust, more or less U-shaped. Valva narrow, somewhat longer than tegumen, slightly broadened medially, narrowed distally and rounded apically; ventral process of valva short, broad, rounded apically. Aedeagus large, heavily sclerotized, straight; vesica short, sack-like, projected ventrally, with two elongated clusters of spinules connected dorsally.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B923690FF8EFF8BC7E3AB1DFE54FE4A" blockId="3.[151,1437,153,682]" box="[199,391,370,394]" pageId="3" pageNumber="449">Female unknown.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C337651BFF8EFF8BC7E3ABFAFAA5FDA2" pageId="3" pageNumber="449" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8B923690FF8EFF8BC7E3ABFAFAA5FDA2" blockId="3.[151,1437,153,682]" pageId="3" pageNumber="449">
<emphasis id="B959EA82FF8EFF8BC7E3ABFAFDD7FE6D" box="[199,516,405,430]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="449" reason="1">
<emphasis id="B959EA82FF8EFF8BC7E3ABFAFE2DFE6D" bold="true" box="[199,510,405,430]" pageId="3" pageNumber="449">Distribution and bionomics</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
The new species was collected at ultraviolet light during two nights at middle November, 
<quantity id="4CD59B75FF8EFF8BC7E1ABD5FEC5FE12" box="[197,278,442,466]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.12318" pageId="3" pageNumber="449" unit="in" value="2017.0">2017 in</quantity>
the Nu Jiang (Salween) river valley in northwestern part of China’s Yunnan Province just on the border with North 
<collectingCountry id="F33A7600FF8EFF8BC7FFABB1FE90FE36" box="[219,323,478,502]" name="Myanmar" pageId="3" pageNumber="449">Myanmar</collectingCountry>
(
<collectingRegion id="49E9F872FF8EFF8BC674ABB1FE0DFE36" box="[336,478,478,502]" country="Myanmar" name="Kachin" pageId="3" pageNumber="449">Kachin State</collectingRegion>
). The new species was collected at altitudes of approximately 1650–2000 meters in a montane primary mixed forest dominated by various deciduous trees, bamboo and bushes. Its closest relative 
<taxonomicName id="4C2D4D13FF8EFF8BC3DDA86DFA4FFDDA" baseAuthorityName="Hampson" baseAuthorityYear="1894" box="[1273,1436,514,538]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Lemyra" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="449" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="melanosoma">
<emphasis id="B959EA82FF8EFF8BC3DDA86DFA4FFDDA" box="[1273,1436,514,538]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="449">L. melanosoma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
inhabits the same valley, but its adults fly in middle of May. Other Chinese species of the genus were collected by the senior author in spring and summer periods and 
<taxonomicName id="4C2D4D13FF8EFF8BC5BFA825FCE1FDA2" authorityName="Saldaitis, Volynkin &amp; Dubatolov" authorityYear="2020" box="[667,818,586,610]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Lemyra" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="449" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="persephone">
<emphasis id="B959EA82FF8EFF8BC5BFA825FCE1FDA2" box="[667,818,586,610]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="449">L. persephone</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the only known autumnal 
<taxonomicName id="4C2D4D13FF8EFF8BC343A825FB6BFDA1" authorityName="Walker" authorityYear="1856" box="[1127,1208,586,609]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Lemyra" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="449" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B959EA82FF8EFF8BC343A825FB6BFDA1" box="[1127,1208,586,609]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="449">Lemyra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species in 
<collectingCountry id="F33A7600FF8EFF8BC20BA825FAA1FDA2" box="[1327,1394,586,610]" name="China" pageId="3" pageNumber="449">China</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C337651BFF8EFF8BC7E3A801FD26FD6A" pageId="3" pageNumber="449" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8B923690FF8EFF8BC7E3A801FD26FD6A" blockId="3.[151,1437,153,682]" pageId="3" pageNumber="449">
<emphasis id="B959EA82FF8EFF8BC7E3A801FE9BFD46" bold="true" box="[199,328,622,646]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="449" reason="1">Etymology.</emphasis>
In the Greek mythology, Persephone is a goddess, Hades’ wife and the queen of the underworld. The species’ name refers to its dark, gloomy wing coloration.
</paragraph>
